SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
a) $SPACE Kepler's Law states that the square of the period, \( P \), is proportional to the cube of the distance, \( d \).  Thus, we have \( P^2 =k d^3 \).  Solving for \( P \) gives
$BR 
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ P= \sqrt{kd^3} = \sqrt{k}d^{3/2} = k_1 d^{3/2} \), where \( k_1 \) is now the constant of proportionality.
$BR $SPACE $BR
For the earth, \( P=365 \) and \( d= 93,000,000 \).  Thus, \( \ 365 = k_1 (93,000,000)^{3/2} \ \), so \( \ k_1 = \frac{365}{(93,000,000)^{3/2}} = 4.1 \cdot 10^{-10} \).  This gives
$BR $SPACE $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ P = \frac{365}{(93,000,000)^{3/2}} \cdot d^{3/2} = 365 \frac{d^{3/2}}{(93,000,000)^{3/2}} = 365 \left( \frac{d}{93,000,000} \right)^{3/2} \ \ \) or \( \ \ P=4.1\cdot 10^{-10}d^{3/2} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR

b) $SPACE For $planet[$i], \( d= $mil[$i] \) miles so we have
$BR $SPACE $BR
\( \ \ \ \ P = 365 \left( \frac{$mil[$i]}{93,000,000} \right)^{3/2} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
which gives \( P \approx $day \) earth days.
$BR
END_SOLUTION


